rectal examination a firm nodule on the right lateral lobe of his prostate is palpable. His prostate specific antigen (PSA) is just above normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Re-check PSA in four to six months","TRUS biopsy of prostate","Radical prostatectomy","Trans-urethral resection of the prostate (TURP)","MRI prostate, followed by transperineal prostate biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPalpation of a hard nodule on DRE is suspicious of carcinoma and a prostate biopsy is needed. \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI-guided biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E can reliably help detect clinically significant prostate cancer and provide information regarding tumor location, volume, grade, and stage. These biopsies are performed via a transperineal approach, and are now recommended as the needle traverses clean skin after antiseptic preparation has been used.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransrectal ultrasound guided prostate biopsy (TRUS biopsy)\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer recommended due to the high risk of septicaemia, with the needle passing through the rectum to reach the prostate. In men with a raised PSA, 70-80% of initial biopsies are negative because of the TRUS sampling nature and limitation (poor sensitivity and specificity) of PSA. 25% of prostate cancer has a normal PSA. \u003Cstrong\u003ERechecking the PSA \u003C/strong\u003Ecould be an option where there was an abnormal PSA result, but no other suspicious features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProstate cancer commonly metastasizes to bone, particularly the vertebrae, but a full body bone scan would be inappropriate at this stage of investigation. While the finding of a hard nodule on DRE is a sinister sign; further investigations should be done before progressing to surgery (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Eradical prostatectomy, TURP).\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENote: A digital rectal examination is no longer recommended as a screening tool for carcinoma of the prostate in asymptomatic men seen in primary care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transperineal prostate biopsy is recommended if suspicious for prostate carcinoma.","MRI can reliably help detect clinically significant prostate cancer and provide information regarding tumor location, volume, grade, and stage"],"references":["Eklund M, J\u00e4derling F, Discacciati A, Bergman M, Annerstedt M, Aly M, et al. MRI-Targeted or Standard Biopsy in Prostate Cancer Screening. N Engl J Med. 2021;385(10):908-920. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34237810/","Pedler K, Kitzing Y, Varol C, Arianayagam M. The current status of MRI in prostate cancer. Aust Fam Physician. 2015;44(4):225-229. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/9d9d92ae-c5e7-416e-b156-74504bdfbb33/The-current-status-of-MRI-in-prostate-cancer.aspx#:~:text=Multiparametric%20MRI%20in%20the%20hands,infancy%20and%20requires%20further%20evaluation.","DRAFT 2025 Guidelines for the Early Detection of Prostate Cancer in Australia. https://www.pcfa.org.au/media/f1ubqz10/draft-2025-guidelines-for-the-early-detection-of-prostate-..."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92210"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"681"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92210"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T09:57:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T09:57:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"681"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109841"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Pract